<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05003a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05003a">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05003a"> 3(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Patrick Crozier / S. Amator / Maximus of Turin / Amahor / Augusta Taurinorum</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The author reproduces lengthy extracts from an article written by Cardinal Moran (in the <cite>Irish Ecclesiastical Record</cite>, Oct., 1866) which identifies the place of St. Patrick&apos;s episcopal consecration as the modern Ivrea, near &lsquo;the imperial city Turin, the <mark><i>Augusta Taurinorum</i></mark> of those times&rsquo;. According to John of Tinmouth St. <mark>Patrick was made bishop</mark> by &lsquo;a chief bishop&rsquo; named <mark>Amator</mark>, whose identity has been problematic. The bishop now tries to establish this:]</font> &ldquo;&hellip; Some one will, perhaps, say that there was no Saint at that time in the north of Italy whose name corresponds with that of Amator &hellip; We reply that there was at this time the great St. <mark>Maximus</mark> ruling the See <mark>of Turin</mark>, which city, in a straight course, is not more distant than a few miles from Ivrea. The name Maximus in the old Celtic form would be precisely <mark>Amahor</mark> &hellip;&rdquo; <small> William Bullen Morris, <a name="WBML" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WBML"><cite title="source">The Life of Saint Patrick Apostle of Ireland</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1890) 110-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Maximus of Turin was a saint, bishop and theological writer (<i>ca.</i> 380-465). </mm> </dd></dl>
